{"title":"Pride and Prejudice: LLM Amplifies Self-Bias in Self-Refinement","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"There is no formal, general way to quantify an LLM’s tendency to favor its own outputs during self-refinement, leading to contradictory findings about whether self-refine helps or hurts.","method":"Define self-bias with two complementary statistics: (i) statistical bias between the LLM’s self-evaluated quality and the true/ground-truth quality, and (ii) distance skewness of the residual distribution E[θ̂]−θ to capture asymmetric over/underestimation. Instantiate task-ground truths per setting: MQM-aligned scores via quantile-mapped BLEURT for machine translation, exact concept coverage for constrained generation, and binary correctness for math reasoning. Run an iterative self-refine protocol that only accepts refinements when the (self-)feedback score improves, enabling bias and skewness tracking across iterations."},{"problem":"LLM self-refine and self-rewarding pipelines can optimize toward falsely perceived improvements due to self-evaluation bias, causing quality to stagnate or degrade.","method":"Empirically compare LLM self-evaluations against reference-based BLEURT and human MQM across six LLMs, four languages, and three tasks, showing universal self-bias that amplifies over iterations; in self-rewarding, increasing the candidate pool size further amplifies bias. Analyze what changes after self-refine with UniEval and style-paraphrasing experiments, finding perceived gains are mainly in fluency/understandability and style alignment rather than actual task objectives, explaining the divergence between self-estimated and true performance."},{"problem":"Mitigating self-bias is necessary to elicit real self-correction and avoid false-positive optimization in self-refine.","method":"Replace self-feedback with external, low-bias feedback using InstructScore, which provides fine-grained error spans, types, and severities with access to references (oracle-like) while leaving corrections to the LLM; this significantly lowers bias during refinement and yields consistent BLEURT gains. Additionally, scale model size (e.g., LLaMA2-70B vs 7B/13B) to improve robustness: larger models exhibit reduced and stabilized self-bias over iterations, enabling more accurate self-assessment and better self-correction."}]}
